{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18424"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114252"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96252"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10244"},{"type":"tags","id":"11265"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114252"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding muscle cross-sectional area?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maximum muscle tension is inversely proportional to its cross-sectional area","Increase in cross-sectional area is primarily due to hyperplasia","Increase in cross-sectional area is primarily due to hypertrophy","Muscle cross-sectional area does not affect muscle strength","Muscle cross-sectional area decreases with resistance training"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMuscle cross-sectional area is a key determinant of muscle strength. An increase in muscle cross-sectional area is primarily due to \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the enlargement of existing muscle fibers. This occurs as a result of resistance training, where muscle fibers increase in size due to the addition of contractile proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, or the formation of new muscle fibers, is not the primary mechanism for increasing muscle cross-sectional area in humans. While it may occur to a limited extent, hypertrophy is the predominant process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximum muscle tension \u003C/strong\u003Eis directly \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportional to its cross-sectional area,\u003C/strong\u003E meaning that as the cross-sectional area increases, so does the potential for generating force. Therefore, the statement that maximum muscle tension is inversely proportional to cross-sectional area is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMuscle cross-sectional area is a critical factor in determining \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscle strength\u003C/strong\u003E, and it typically increases with resistance training, not decreases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Muscle hypertrophy, not hyperplasia, is the primary mechanism for increasing muscle cross-sectional area.","Maximum muscle tension is directly proportional to its cross-sectional area."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 6; pg. 90","Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96252"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96252"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:16:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:16:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114252"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}}